@taranjeet The thing is that `created` and `modified` fields have a default value set to the current time: https://github.com/jazzband/django-model-utils/blob/master/model_utils/fields.py#L12-L36.

Now, if I create a new Aggregator object for an existing `(user, course_key, block_key, aggregation_name)` object, its `created` and `modified` values are not going to be what they are in the database. So the Aggregator objects that are going to be passed to `bulk_create_or_update` and are going to be set in `self.aggregators` are going to be invalid. The difference with `create_or_update` is that the later is passed data with differentiation between the key fields and others and as you noted returns an object that can put into `self.aggregators`. Yes, this does work here because of how `bulk_create_or_update` is internally implemented but callers should not assume anything about that and because they are not currently looking at the `created` or `modified` fields.

As far as I see the only thing needed here is adding a check that if there is an existing object, four of its fields are updated. Otherwise a new object is created as is happening here already.

Instead of using `true` and `false` in the tests, please consider creating and using constants like
```
bool const strings_as_strings = false;
bool const strings_as_dictionaries = true;
```
That should make the tests more readable.
